]}
{"messages":[
  {
    "role":"system",
    "content":"You explain how to transfer records."
  },
  {
    "role":"user",
    "content":"How do I transfer my records from my old doctor to you?"
  },
  {
    "role":"assistant",
    "content":"To transfer your medical records, you’ll need to complete a release of information form. You can fill it out in our office or download it from our website and upload it through the portal. Once we have your signed form, we’ll fax or electronically request your records from your previous provider. The process can take a few days to a couple of weeks, depending on their office."
  }
]}
{"messages":[
  {
    "role":"system",
    "content":"You answer exam preparation questions."
  },
  {
    "role":"user",
    "content":"What should I bring to my first appointment?"
  },
  {
    "role":"assistant",
    "content":"For your first visit, please bring a photo ID, your insurance card, a list of your current medications (including doses), and any relevant medical records if you have them. If you completed new patient forms online, you don’t need to fill them out again. We also recommend arriving 15–20 minutes early so we can verify your information before your appointment."
  }
]}
{"messages":[
  {
    "role":"system",
    "content":"You give realistic guidance on telehealth limitations."
  },
  {
    "role":"user",
    "content":"Can everything be done over telehealth instead of in person?"
  },
  {
    "role":"assistant",
    "content":"Telehealth is very convenient, but not everything can be done remotely. Visits that require a physical exam, procedures, vaccinations, or certain tests still need to be in person. Many follow-ups, medication checks, and result reviews can be handled by video or phone. Our scheduling team can help you choose the right visit type based on your needs and your provider’s recommendations."
  }
]}
{"messages":[
  {
    "role":"system",
    "content":"You help patients understand when to use urgent care."
  },
  {
    "role":"user",
    "content":"It’s the weekend. Can I see someone, or do I have to wait until Monday?"
  },
  {
    "role":"assistant",
    "content":"Our regular clinic is closed on weekends, but we recommend urgent care for issues that can’t wait until Monday but aren’t life-threatening—for example, minor injuries, ear pain, or mild asthma flare-ups. For severe symptoms like chest pain, difficulty breathing, or signs of stroke, please call 911 or go to the nearest emergency room immediately. You can also send us a portal message, and we’ll follow up on the next business day."
  }
]}
{"messages":[
  {
    "role":"system",
